Introduction

The dataset used in this analysis is John Hopkins’ Covid-19 dataset found here: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/tree/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series. The data is presented in two documents: one for cumulative confirmed cases and the other for cumulative confirmed deaths for most countries worldwide. This information is pulled from a multitude of sources including governments and the WHO, and synthesized in this document. Values are updated daily by the owners of the database.

Both number of confirmed cases and number of confirmed deaths will be important figures in this analysis. Number of deaths is the more reliable statistic as confirmed cases relies on testing frequency and capacity. The number of confirmed cases is therefore a lower bound for the number of actual cases of COVID-19. Changes in confirmed cases could also be due to an increase in testing, so these numbers should be viewed with caution.

The importance of analyses like these cannot be understated. After watching the news daily in the last two weeks, this dataset was main source for most of the statistics presented. The number of confirmed cases, and how fast that number is growing, has been on the forefront of people’s minds worldwide. This dataset wields immense power and is extremely important to determine the severity of the situation that we find ourselves in, and is essential for strategic response.

Results

Let’s begin by looking at the progression of Hubei province. With strict contact tracing, complete lockdown of all non-essential business, and a travel ban, China was able to stem the flow of the rate of infection in about eight weeks. The death rate hovers just below 4% for China. This pattern follows the standard S curve of infectious diseases where infection rate begins exponential, then looks more logarithmic past the inflection point.

Let’s look at Italy.One look at the number of cases on the left side and it becomes clear that this graph is worse than the previous. Italy has surpassed Hubei, and soon to be China, in number of cases and deaths. Not only that, but it is still experiencing exponential growth, meaning the rate of increase is increasing. Let’s look at a plot of how exponential Italy’s cases and deaths are increasing.

Here, a number above 0 suggests an exponential increase in the type of report. Although both deaths and cases are still increasing exponentially, the rate at which the number of new reports are occuring is falling. Below 0, the disease can, in one respect, be considered under control, because the number of new cases is not building upon itself exponentially.

Here there are two major trends I would like to point out. The first is obviously how dramatic the rate of increase in the United States is. Caught unprepared, the Virus was able to establish a foothold in NYC, a city with high population density, before society and the government implimented proper spread suppression procedures.

The other example I wish to highlight is Hubei’s (Labeled China in the plot) line. The completed curve of the rate of the rate of increase will meander through the x-axis, past 0, and into negative numbers until new cases dwindle to almost 0 (barring another outbreak, which is still possible). It’s difficult to tell how close the US is to this transition, and more advanced models should be referenced for such information.

Here is the same plot, but for deaths. Spain has struggled to contain the number of deaths.

Which countries are experiencing exponential growth? The following graph, inspired by Aatish Bhatia (https://aatishb.com/covidtrends/), graphs cumulative cases against daily new cases summed over the week prior to that day. The straighter the line of a given country, the more similar to true exponential growth in deaths or cases that country has. The countries you see falling off that straight line pattern are beginning to see a slow down in the number of new cases. China’s big bump was due to the one day redefinition of COVID-19.

Discussion

The conclusions of this report are changing daily with the updates of the dataset. Centralized datasets such as these are not the only information source which should inspire action, but they can play a significant role. Without data analysis during times of crisis such as this, we are relying on the individual beliefs of people. When an issue’s scope is at the level of the entire world, no amount of intuition will ever surpass the insights of large data.

This is not to say that data is infalliable. When looking into the sources of data and methods of data collection for this dataset, It becomes clear that it is far from perfect. Each country’s numbers rely on the government’s honor that reports are valid, and assumptions must be made about the confidence of data collection at multiple levels of the pipeline.

Further work is being relentlessly pursued globally. As more data come out, more questions are able to be answered. We are still unsure of the exact case fatality rate, the exact spread rate, or, perhaps most importantly, what measures best defend human life.
